article.description: Asjha Jones scored a career-high 22 points and the Sun set an Eastern Conference record for wins by beating the Sting 78-69 on Saturday.
article.headline: Sun shine, set Eastern Conference record for wins
article.linkText: Sun shine, set Eastern Conference record for wins
article.story:
CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Connecticut coach Mike Thibault wanted
his team playing well going into the playoffs.

Asjha Jones scored a career-high 22 points and the Sun set an
Eastern Conference record for wins by beating the Charlotte Sting
78-69 on Saturday.

Lindsay Whalen added 18 points and Nykesha Sales scored 14 for
the Sun (26-8), who topped Detroit's 25-9 mark in 2003.
Connecticut, which has home-court advantage throughout the
playoffs, will visit Detroit to open the first round Wednesday.

"We wanted to finish the season strong and not get any injuries
tonight," Thibault said. "Plus, our players were aware we could
have the best Eastern Conference record ever."

Sheri Sam scored 21 points for the Sting (6-28), who had their
two-game winning snapped and finished with the worst record in team
history. Charlotte's previous worst mark was 8-24 in 2000.

"I don't think we need to do much," said Sting rookie Janel
McCarville, the No. 1 pick in the draft. "I think it's just a
matter of playing together."

Sales hit a 3-pointer and Whalen had a 3-point play in a 9-2 run
to start the second half that put Connecticut ahead 55-38. The
Sting, who shot 28 percent, got within six points in the final
minute.

"Tough night," said Sting coach Muggsy Bogues, who was 3-7
after taking over for Trudi Lacey. "When you shoot like that
you're not going to beat anybody in this league. They didn't quit
and we cut it to six, but the ball didn't bounce our way."

Thibault was able to rest many of his starters over the final 10
minutes as the Sun won their second straight game after a two-game
losing streak.

"We tried different groups and combinations so we could figure
out who would be on our playoff roster," Thibault said.

Connecticut played without starting guard Katie Douglas, who sat
out as a precaution with a sore back. The Sun used a quirk in the
WNBA rules and placed Douglas on the injured list and activated
center Laura Summerton. They will be able to activate Douglas on
Sunday when playoff rosters are set.

The Sun, showing no ill effects from an early morning flight
following a home win over Washington on Friday night, used an 8-1
run to take a 39-31 lead on Sales' putback with 3:30 left in the
first half.

"We didn't want to come here and take this game lightly,"
Whalen said. "We started off slow, but had a great run in each
half."

It marked the Sting's final game at the Charlotte Coliseum. The
Sting, who were 84-60 in nine seasons in their old home, will play
in the new Charlotte Bobcats Arena in 2006.

"It's a sad day and a good day," said Bogues, the Charlotte
Hornets' starting point guard in the early days of the Coliseum.
"This was a wonderful place when the Hornets started. I remember
the first game we played and we lost by 40, but the fans gave us a
standing ovation.

"That's what we're trying to get back to, that family
atmosphere, and we're going to do that with the Sting."
